SIMPLE: manifestation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manifestation
<hw>Man`i*fes*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>manifestatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>manifestation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of manifesting or disclosing, or the state of
being manifested; discovery to the eye or to the
understanding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which manifests; a phenomenon which gives
evidence of something hidden; exhibition; display; revelation; <as>as,
the <ex>manifestation</ex> of God's power in creation</as>; the delayed
<ex>manifestation</ex> of a disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The secret manner in which acts of mercy ought to be performed,
requires this public <qex>manifestation</qex> of them at the great
day.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The materialization or apparition of a spirit; -- a
phenomenon claimed to be seen by spiritualists.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>manifest destiny</ent>⟦br⟧
